I can help with that. To create a simple counter using JavaScript, you can use the `while` loop and a variable to keep track of the current iteration.

Here's an example code snippet:
```javascript
let i = 0;
let count = 0;

function createCounter() {
    while (i < 10) { // Change the upper limit as needed
        console.log(`Iteration ${i}: Count - ${count}`);
        i++;
        count++;
    }
}

createCounter();
```
This code will print out the iteration number and the current counter value for each iteration, until it reaches the specified upper limit.

If you want to implement a more complex counter that increments every time a specific condition is met, you can use a nested loop structure:
```javascript
function createCounter(condition) {
    let i = 0;
    while (i < 10) { 
        if (condition(i)) {
            console.log(`Iteration ${i}: Count - ${count}`);
            count++;
        }
        i++;
    }
}
```
You can call this function with a condition to be met, like `createCounter(() => i > 5)`.

Please note that these examples assume you have a basic understanding of JavaScript and the concept of loops. If you need more complex counter functionality or additional features, I'd be happy to help!

